  by past practice) or like deep conventions (constitutive of forms of life)? Marmor's distinction
  between arbitrary conventions and non-arbitrary customs parallels discussions of tradition's
  claimed authority.

  POSITION: Legal and social philosophy extending Lewis. Conventions as constitutive rules
  and coordination devices, distinguished from customs by arbitrariness and from norms by
  dependence on practice.
  },
  keywords = {convention, custom, constitutive-rules, Marmor, Medium}
}

@book{gilbert1989social,
  author = {Gilbert, Margaret},
  title = {On Social Facts},
  year = {1989},
  publisher = {Princeton University Press},
  address = {Princeton},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Gilbert develops her influential "plural subject" account of social phenomena,
  arguing that collective phenomena (including conventions, social norms, and group beliefs)
  are constituted by joint commitments. When people form a plural subject, they commit together
  to uphold certain beliefs, intentions, or practices as a body. This joint commitment creates
  obligations and normative expectations that cannot be reduced to individual commitments.
  Gilbert critiques Lewisian accounts of convention as unable to capture the normative force
  and obligation characteristic of many social practices.

  RELEVANCE: Gilbert's plural subject theory is foundational for social ontology and raises
  important questions for understanding tradition. If traditions are social phenomena, do they
  require joint commitments among participants? Or can traditions exist through aggregated
  individual participation without collective commitment? Gilbert's emphasis on normativity
  and obligation in social practices suggests traditions may have a social ontology similar to
  conventions or social norms. For a project on the concept of tradition, Gilbert provides
  conceptual resources for understanding tradition's social reality.

  POSITION: Social ontology and philosophy of social science. Plural subject theory emphasizing
  joint commitment as constitutive of social phenomena including conventions and collective
  practices.
  },
  keywords = {Gilbert, plural-subject, social-ontology, collective-commitment, Medium}
}

@book{searle1995construction,
  author = {Searle, John R.},
  title = {The Construction of Social Reality},
  year = {1995},
  publisher = {Free Press},
  address = {New York},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Searle provides a systematic account of social ontology, arguing that
  institutional facts (money, property, marriage) are created through collective intentionality
  and constitutive rules of the form "X counts as Y in context C." Social reality is constructed
  through collective recognition and acceptance of status functions. Unlike Gilbert, Searle
  emphasizes collective intentionality (we-intentions) rather than joint commitments, and he
  grounds institutional reality in human intentionality without requiring explicit agreements.
  Status functions persist through collective acceptance even when individual participants change.

  RELEVANCE: Searle's framework is widely used in social ontology and raises questions about
  tradition's ontological status. Are traditions institutional facts constituted by collective
  acceptance? If so, what is the "X counts as Y" structure? Perhaps: "This practice (X) counts
  as authoritative tradition (Y) in our community (C)"? Searle's emphasis on collective acceptance
  and status functions helps explain how traditions can persist across generations despite
  changing participants. His framework is essential for situating tradition within contemporary
  social ontology debates.

  POSITION: Social ontology emphasizing collective intentionality and constitutive rules.
  Institutional facts created through collective assignment of status functions, persisting
  through collective acceptance.
  },
  keywords = {Searle, social-ontology, collective-intentionality, institutional-facts, High}
}

@book{tuomela2002philosophy,
  author = {Tuomela, Raimo},
