  function as rule-governed communication systems within closed communities. Traditions establish
  defined principles of communication for members and rules of inclusion for potential new
  members. The rational structure of tradition lies in its systematic organization of meaning
  and practice, not in the content of what is transmitted. This shifts focus from tradition's
  content to its structural properties as a communication system.

  RELEVANCE: Grad's pragmatic approach offers a distinctive angle on tradition, focusing on
