  RELEVANCE: This paper addresses a crucial problem for contemporary political philosophy: how
  to think about tradition in pluralistic, multicultural societies. It goes beyond single-
  tradition frameworks (MacIntyre's tradition-constituted rationality) to ask about relationships
  between traditions. The concept of mediating institutions and philosophy's role as second-order
  tradition is philosophically rich. For the research project, this illustrates how tradition
  is being reconceptualized to address contemporary political challenges of diversity, moving
  beyond older conservative or hermeneutic models.

  POSITION: Critical social theory drawing on Dumont and Bannerji. Philosophy as mediating
  institution between traditions, addressing tradition in pluralistic contexts and critiquing
  hegemonic tradition-protection.
  },
  keywords = {mediating-institutions, tradition-plurality, Dumont, multiculturalism, Medium}
}

@article{ambord2009hermeneutics,
  author = {Ambord, Daniel},
  title = {The Hermeneutics of Tradition: Political Implications of a Philosophical Legacy},
  journal = {Epoché: A Journal for the History of Philosophy},
  year = {2009},
  volume = {13},
  number = {2},
  pages = {373--395},
  note = {
