@book{lutz2004tradition,
  author = {Lutz, Christopher Stephen},
  title = {Tradition in the Ethics of Alasdair MacIntyre: Relativism, Thomism, and Philosophy},
  year = {2004},
  publisher = {Lexington Books},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Lutz provides a comprehensive analysis of MacIntyre's conception of tradition as central to his ethical and political philosophy. The book examines MacIntyre's response to relativism through the idea of "tradition-constituted rationality"—the view that all rational inquiry occurs within traditions, yet traditions can rationally evaluate themselves and engage competing traditions. Lutz explores how MacIntyre's Thomistic commitments shape his understanding of tradition and how this avoids both relativism and absolutism.

  RELEVANCE: MacIntyre offers one of the most sophisticated contemporary defenses of tradition's epistemic authority while avoiding conservative dogmatism. His work is crucial for the project because it shows how tradition can be defended philosophically without rejecting rational criticism or comparative evaluation. MacIntyre's framework allows tradition to be both constitutive of rationality and subject to rational revision—a position that transcends simple conservative/progressive dichotomies.

