  CORE ARGUMENT: Warnke provides a systematic exposition and critical assessment of Gadamer's philosophical hermeneutics, with particular attention to how Gadamer's rehabilitation of tradition relates to questions of rationality and critique. She defends Gadamer against charges of conservatism by showing that effective-historical consciousness enables critical reflection on tradition, not just passive acceptance. Warnke explicates how Gadamer's account allows for both belonging to tradition and critical distance from it.

  RELEVANCE: This is the standard secondary source on Gadamer's views of tradition and reason in English-language scholarship. Warnke clarifies Gadamer's position on the Enlightenment critique and shows how his hermeneutics provides resources for rational criticism while avoiding both Enlightenment foundationalism and relativism. Essential for understanding the internal tensions in Gadamer's account and its implications for political theory.

  POSITION: Sympathetic interpretation of Gadamer. Argues his hermeneutics is not conservative but rather offers a non-foundationalist account of how tradition enables critique.
  },
  keywords = {Gadamer, hermeneutics-tradition, interpretation, High}
}

@incollection{habermas1977hermeneutic,
  author = {Habermas, Jürgen},
  title = {The Hermeneutic Claim to Universality},
