  RELEVANCE: Provides focused analysis of the universality claim central to Gadamer's philosophy and to debates about whether tradition-based understanding can be self-critical. The question of universality connects directly to whether hermeneutics can address political questions about ideology, power, and emancipation or whether these require different rational resources. Important for seeing the stakes of the debate beyond narrow epistemological concerns.

