  RELEVANCE: This is the most thorough secondary treatment of MacIntyre's views on tradition and rationality. D'Andrea clarifies MacIntyre's complex relationship to the Enlightenment project, showing both his critique of its pretensions to tradition-independent rationality and his retention of the ideal of rational progress. Essential for understanding how MacIntyre's position differs from both Gadamer's hermeneutics and liberal rationalism, and for seeing the political implications of tradition-constituted rationality for contemporary debates.

