  RELEVANCE: Illuminates the Aristotelian background to both Gadamer's and MacIntyre's accounts of tradition-based rationality. Dunne shows how the recovery of phronesis challenges Enlightenment conceptions of reason as method-driven and universal. His analysis of the Gadamer-Habermas debate focuses on whether practical wisdom (phronesis) can be separated from tradition or whether it is necessarily tradition-bound. Essential for understanding the Aristotelian roots of contemporary defenses of tradition.

